            "metadata": {
              "app_version": "7.2.0",
              "chart": "redis",
              "first_deployed": 1752458456,
              "last_deployed": 1752458456,
              "name": "redis-app",
              "namespace": "default",
              "notes": "CHART NAME: redis\nCHART VERSION: 18.0.0\nAPP VERSION: 7.2.0\n\n** Please be patient while the chart is being deployed **\n\nRedis\u0026reg; can be accessed on the following DNS names from within your cluster:\n\n    redis-app-master.default.svc.cluster.local for read/write operations (port 6379)\n    redis-app-replicas.default.svc.cluster.local for read-only operations (port 6379)\n\n\n\nTo connect to your Redis\u0026reg; server:\n\n1. Run a Redis\u0026reg; pod that you can use as a client:\n\n   kubectl run --namespace default redis-client --restart='Never'  --image docker.io/bitnami/redis:7.2.0-debian-11-r0 --command -- sleep infinity\n\n   Use the following command to attach to the pod:\n\n   kubectl exec --tty -i redis-client \\\n   --namespace default -- bash\n\n2. Connect using the Redis\u0026reg; CLI:\n   redis-cli -h redis-app-master\n   redis-cli -h redis-app-replicas\n\nTo connect to your database from outside the cluster execute the following commands:\n\n    kubectl port-forward --namespace default svc/redis-app-master 6379:6379 \u0026\n    redis-cli -h 127.0.0.1 -p 6379\n",
              "revision": 1,
              "values": "{\"auth\":{\"enabled\":false},\"master\":{\"persistence\":{\"enabled\":true}},\"replica\":{\"replicaCount\":1}}",
              "version": "18.0.0"
            },
